Romi Feedback Control Special Case 1:¶

$$ \ddot{x}_{romi} = \dot{U} = \frac{a_{0U}}{a_{1U}} U + \frac{b_{0U}}{a_{1U}} V_{in} $$ $$ V_{in} = K_U (d) = K_U \left(x_d-x_{romi}\right)$$ $$\therefore \ddot{x}_{romi} = \frac{a_{0U}}{a_{1U}} U + \frac{b_{0U}}{a_{1U}} K_U \left(x_d-x_{romi}\right)$$

Romi Feedback Control Special Case 2:¶

$$ \ddot{\psi} = \frac{a_{0\psi}}{a_{1\psi}} \dot{\psi} + \frac{b_{0\psi}}{a_{1\psi}} \Delta V_{in} $$ $$ \Delta V_{in} = K_\psi \left(\psi_g-\psi \right)$$ $$\therefore \ddot{\psi} = \frac{a_{0\psi}}{a_{1\psi}} \dot{\psi} + \frac{b_{0\psi}}{a_{1\psi}} K_\psi \left(\psi_g-\psi\right)$$

The Occupancy Grid Map¶

An occupancy grid map, in its simplest form, is just a matrix of ones and zeros. Normally, a "1" in a matrix cell means that the cell is "occupied" and a zero means that it is not. Consider the example in the figure below.

Converting between true coordinates and map cell indices¶

Suppose we are considering a cell at row $i$ and column $j$ in an occupancy grid map $\mathcal{M}(m\times n)$, where (for now) we assume the map is square and $m=n$. We will further assume standard "map" coordinates apply, with an origin in the bottom left with $X$ pointing along the columns, and $Y$ pointing upward along the rows. Note that this means that the point $X=0,Y=0$ will be at the very bottom edge of the cell at row $m$, column $0$.

Using this definition, the $i,j$ cell's centroid in "true" allocentric coordinates will be located at:

\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} ^Ax_c &= \frac{D}{2n} + j\frac{D}{n} \\ ^Ay_c &= \frac{L}{m}\left(m-i-\frac{1}{2}\right) \end{aligned} \end{equation}

To go the other way, and turn a "true" allocentric position $(^Ax,^Ay)$ into a "cell" membership $(i,j)$, we can use the following equations:

\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} j &= int\left( \frac{n}{D}\left(^Ax-\frac{D}{2n}\right) \right) \\ i &= int\left(m-\frac{1}{2} - y\frac{m}{L} \right) \end{aligned} \end{equation}

Using maps: Planning a path around obstacles to reach a goal¶

Consider the following map, where the Romi's goal is to get the Apple. The green path is shorter by two cells. But how would the Romi "know" this? How could this be determined automatically?

Dijkstra's Algorithm¶

Lots of very smart people have worked on path planning for a long time, and the algorithm we will start with here is called Dijkstra's algorithm. It was invented in 1959. There's a great blog post about this algorithm with an implementation that has been loaded into the Week11 sample world of your ES302_Webots repository. These notes are based on that blog post. You should read the original post!!

Dijkstra's Algorithm¶

Dijkstra's algorithm looks at a grid map as a "graph" (in the mathematical sense). In a "graph" representation of the occupancy grid, each cell is a "node" in the graph, and it is connected by "edges" to each node "above" it, "below" it, to its "left," and to its "right." This is shown below.
